Fix CVE-2021-26540: URL validation bypass using backslash characters

Browsers (particularly Chrome) accept backslash (\) as a substitute for
forward slash (/) at the start of URLs. This allows attackers to bypass
URL scheme validation by using URLs like "/\example.com" which browsers
interpret as "//example.com" (protocol-relative URL).

This patch adds URL normalization to the naughtyHref function to convert
any backslashes to forward slashes and remove whitespace at the start of
URLs before validation, preventing the bypass.

Origin: upstream, https://github.com/apostrophecms/sanitize-html/commit/6012524e7824a2c8f6782b2bc5f93b1261723403
Bug: https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2021-26540

